english:
  title: Inscription for Yangchon Village
  author: Lee Cheom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yin and Yang arise from the movement and stillness of the Great Ultimate, bearing a relation of opposition that admits no change. Yet human nature holds both goodness and evil, and the principles of the world contain both fortune and misfortune—this is the division between Yang and Yin, virtue and its lack. When the Sage composed the Book of Changes, he placed the pure Yang hexagram first and the pure Yin hexagram second, thereby showing that neither can be dispensed with alone. The tenth month has no Yang lines, yet it is called a Yang month—this too reflects the Sage's intent to sustain Yang and restrain Yin. Yang in virtue becomes Benevolence and Propriety; in the seasons it becomes Spring and Summer—from it all things draw their beginning and arise. Though it may sometimes lie beneath the multitude of Yin, it must inevitably ascend. Thus we see that Heaven's Way cycles endlessly and Yang can never be exhausted.

    Master Kwon of Yeongga devoted himself from youth to the Six Classics, penetrating their meaning, and took special care with the study of the Book of Changes. Understanding the principle of Yang, he wished never to forget it even in idle moments, so he named his dwelling Yangchon Village. I, Ssangmae, humbly compose this inscription.

    The inscription reads:
    How splendid is this Way—its principle shines clear!
    The body takes its stand after Heaven's formation,
    Yet its use precedes all Heaven's beginning.
    Only the sage and the worthy flow with their nature,
    Yet also restore themselves to their nature's source.
    Strive onward, Master Kwon,
    And investigate the genesis of virtue's stirring.
  footnotes:
    - The ten hexagrams of the I Ching (Book of Changes) referenced here represent the foundational principles of yin-yang cosmology central to Neo-Confucian thought.
    - The tenth lunar month (called a 'Yang month' despite having no Yang lines) symbolizes the eternal return and circulation of Yang force even in apparent absence—a key concept in the author's philosophy.
    - Ssangmae (雙梅子, 'Double Plum Master') was a pen name, possibly referring to Lee Cheom himself or another scholar-poet of the era.
